Output: Virtual machines (VM) emulate real physical machines. They run underneath a more powerful (and more vulnerable) operating system.  When an iPhone runs an app that is designed to run on iOS, it does not literally need to emulate the actual architecture of iOS, because it can use a simulated version of the actual system.
For example, iOS runs on an x86 CPU. iOS applications are compiled for the iPhone and this requires that the application is compiled for ARM CPUs. This is because the emulator simulates the actual processors that apps will run on when actually installed on your phone.  iOS apps are also compiled for ARM because the architecture of the CPUs in iOS phones isn’t all that different from the hardware in your phone. They are compiled to run on an ARM for the emulator.
If the app is designed to run on other CPU architectures, it needs to be compiled with a compiler that supports multiple architectures. There is a program called libGCC which is a C compiler with support for multiple CPU architectures. This allows developers to compile an app, which can run under either OS X or iOS.

This application implements a version of the programming language Lua for smartwatches and smartphones.

### Usage:

* Run the app on the phone.
* Place the watch on the charger.
* Choose a script between the available presets.
* Tap "Run" on the phone.

### Implementation details:

Lua 5.3.5 is the Lua engine implemented in this application, and [Lua-for-Android][1] is the Lua interpreter used to provide the graphical interface.

Because the watch lacks an actual keyboard, the app communicates with it via the Android Debug Bridge ("adb") protocol. This implies that any application can be transferred and executed on an Android app that is targeted to the "watch" platform family. The Lua interpreter is hosted as a Java Web service that allows other application components to communicate with the Lua engine.

The Lua engine is hosted on two separate processes on the phone. The first process (the Lua interpreter) communicates with the debugger via adb. The Lua engine actually runs in parallel in a second process, allowing the interpreter to do its work, while the Lua app can communicate with the Lua process through an interprocess communication pipe.

[1]: http://code.google.com/p/luaforandroid/
